Current CLR implementation have two OpCodes that works with virtual methods: 
ldvirtftn -> "vtable offset"
"vtable offset" -> callvirt

In this feature request new OpCode is introduced: "ldvirtftnptr".
This opcode should resolve direct pointer to the virtual/interface method.
ldvirtftnptr -> "pointer to method"
"pointer to method" -> call (with load "this" object as a first argument)

With this CLR improvement, compilers will be able to eliminate performance penalty of virtual method call.

For example:
```CSharp
public class A
{
    public virtual int GetValue()
    {
         return 1;
    }
}

public class B: A
{
    public override int GetValue()
    {
         return base.GetValue() * 2;
    }
}

// Client code that is sensitive to a virtual method call performance.
A b = new B();
int sum = 0;

// resolve direct pointer to machine code of b.GetValue() implementation and store it in the stack
// IL:   ldvirtftnptr  b.GetValue() 
for (int i = 0; i < 100; i++)
{
     // IL:  load "b" as the first argument to subsequent call
     // IL:   call (0x28 opcode)  with the direct pointer to machine code of b.GetValue() implementation
     sum += b.GetValue();
}

```
It's a kind of devirtualization.
The same idea is described here http://blog.llvm.org/2017/03/devirtualization-in-llvm-and-clang.html and implemented in LLVM since version 4.0.
It's referenced here as "Devirtualization of function calls inside loops"

LINQ to objects will receive huge performance improvement from this feature.

See #21298 

